description.text:
This came from my partner wanting to hang the heart on her belt while attending Steampunk events and my wanting to find a way to hold the heart better while turning it. Being clumsy, I kept dropping it.
This is from "Emmett's Screwless Heart Gears" and the stand is by Mjolnir's "Stand for Emmett's Screwless Heart Gears"

Since I already had the hearts printed, I manually made the modifications to the parts. I replaced the top pin (short) with a 1/4" x 1-3/4" cotterless hitch pin with D-ring.
1) use a 1/4" drill bit and drill the hole in the top center piece all the way through. (When I get a chance I will update the stl file extending the shaft all the way through. The STL file included is unmodified).
2) Insert a 1/4" x 1-3/4" cotterless hitch pin through the top piece and into the center piece. Mark where the top of the top center piece is on the hitch pin. 
3) remove and glue a washer on the hitch pin at the mark you made. If you don't do this, then when you rotate the heart the center piece travels upwards.
4) add some glue to the inside center piece and reinsert the hitch pin with the top center piece in place.
5) let the glue dry.
Now you just hold the bottom of the heart and use the hitch pin to twist away!
At some point I will probably design and print a piece to replace the metal hitch pin. My first attempt at doing so was unsuccessful. I think instead of printing the pin/key with a hollow center it should be solid in order to make it strong enough to turn the heart gears.

description.text:
This is a mounting bracket to fix the SainSmart Megatronics LCD12864 onto Mendel style printers Fits on:
  • Mendel-Style printer (M8 threaded-rod frame)
  • Mendelmax printer
  • others...

Mendel

  • Print the three parts

    • Holder (for standard M8 hex head screw OR cylinder head screw)
    • Nutholder
    • End (for standard M3 hex head screw OR cylinder head screw)

  • Buy Vitamins / additional parts:

    • 1 M8 x 120 cylinder head screw (or standard hex head cap screw with washer)
    • 1 M8 nut
    • 1 M8 spring washer
    • 2 M3 x 20 cylinder head screws (or M3 x 25 with philips machine head)
    • 2 M3 nuts
  • Assemble the parts
    • Put the M8 screw in the holder (there is a bigger hole for the cylinder head at the left side of the mouting).
    • Put the spring washer on the threaded end of the screw.
    • M8 nut and M3 nuts go into the specific holes of the nut holder part.
    • Connect mounting and Nut holder with the M8 screw.
    • Put the free end of the nut holder on a threaded rod of your printer. Put the end part from the other side of the threaded rod and fix the mounting-nut-holder and the end part with two M3 screws.
    • Finally you can tighten the M8 screw so that the angle of the display can be changed by hand.
    • Mendelmax

  • Print two parts

    • Holder (for standard M8 hex head screw OR cylinder head screw)
    • Nutholder for Mendelmax

  • Buy Vitamins / additional parts:

    • 1 M8 x 120 cylinder head screw (or standard hex head cap screw with washer)
    • 1 M8 nut
    • 1 M8 spring washer
    • 2 M5 x 16 cylinder head screws
    • 2 M5 washers
    • 2 M5 T-Slot nuts
  • Assemble the parts
    • Put the M8 screw in the holder (there is a bigger hole for the cylinder head at the left side of the mouting).
    • Put the spring washer on the threaded end of the screw.
    • Connect mounting and Nut holder with the M8 screw.
    • Attach the Nut holder to the printerframe by using 2x M5 screws and T-Slot nuts.
    • Finally you can tighten the M8 screw so that the angle of the display can be changed by hand.

comments.author: TwilightLegoTrainMLPBoyZ1

comments.text: Great thanks.  What does .mdl stand for and what would count as those?
comments.author: TrotskytheHellSteed

comments.text: I don't remember what .mdl stands for but it's easy to look up, it's the standard file format for SFM models. An SFM model comes with a whole bunch of various pieces of information, but as far as I know all of the 3D data is stored in the .mdl file. Don't delete the files around it until you've finished converting though, as I think there is a piece or two of information required from the surrounding files. At least according to my converter. Converted SFM files usually come out pretty nice with no gaping holes or other issues. However they still need to be smoothed out and patched up for the small scale, so use the fix for minimum thickness option in meshmixer once you've shrunk stuff down to scale. That will help buff things out and make it so you can actually print your part. After that, check over manually for any weak spots and patch those, then your good to go.

Print all parts with 15% fill and double perimeter.
this is to cut weight.
The feet should be printed with support material on, because of the part that will go into the aluminium tube.
The 2x aluminium 15mm square tube L=800mm, wall thickness 1.5mm, are cut out half in the middle to fit into each other and form a cross.
I post it as a SolidWorks Part and pdf.
The motor pods are at a 600 mm pitch.
The arms will stick out 100mm to protect the props. You need about 12 40mm M4 hex socket head cap screws and 16 nylock nuts and some M4 washers to protect the plastic. description.text:
This adapter works with both EF and EF-S lenses.
The difference between the flange distance of M4/3 and Canon EF is 24.75mm, which is the main dimension of this part. The EF mount is modeled largely off of existing extension tubes on Thingiverse, and the M4/3 mount is based off of existing M4/3 adapters, and some trial and error. A technical drawing with all the critical dimensions is available, feel free to use to create more adapters. If you are looking to create adapters for the Micro 4/3 mount, I can provide part files and advice for designing them.
The locking pin recess should work on most M4/3 cameras, I can verify that it works on a Panasonic GH4/5.

Update 6/6/2016:
I have added a locking pin for the EF side of the adapter, which works by first attaching the EF lens to the adapter, inserting the locking pin, the attaching the adapter to the MFT camera. The pin will be held in place when the adapter is attached to the camera, removing the need for a spring-loaded pin and release mechanism. This design was suggested to me by Wisnaeme (https://www.thingiverse.com/Wisnaeme), and it's a brilliant solution I don't think I would have come up with on my own, so many thanks to him.
The part files for the updated design are mftef locking pin cut.stl (the main adapter body) and mftef locking pin.stl (the locking pin itself) There is also the option to print a file without the pin and glue in a metal rod (2mm) for a stronger locking pin.

Representación física del teorema binomial Puede acompañarse con una representación gráfica en la pizarra del cuadrado (a+b)² que puede ser formado con sus componentes. Y luego mostrar la distributiva, para corroborar que se forma un cubo perfecto.

Pensamiento deductivo La actividad empezaría mostrando los componentes por separado, identificando el tamaño de "a" y el tamaño de "b". Luego, invitar a los chicos a que formen una figura regular con todas las piezas. Cuando se llegue al cubo, hacer la suma de todas las aristas, demostrando que es un cubo de lado (a+b)(a+b)(a+b) => (a+b)³. Luego en el pizarrón arrancando de (a+b)³ se aplica la distributiva para llegar a la expresión que dan origen a los cubos y prismas rectangulares.

title: Raise3D N2 And N2+ Dual Titan Etruder

description.text:
PB 3D Design Dual Titan Extruder For Raise3d N2 and N2+
Link to the post on Raise3D community: http://forum.raise3d.com/viewtopic.php?f=4&t=1579

Technical data:
Weight with 2x Nema 17 34mm steeper motors 540g, Original extruder 879g.
Total Height: 118mm, Original extruder 135mm.
Total Width: 89mm, Original extruder 74mm.
Total Dept: 72mm, Original extruder 68mm.
No restriction of print volume, still original specification after upgrade.
Designed in Solid Works 2016.

Necessary changes to fit this Extruder:
Drag chain needs to be one link longer, I borrowed on link from the heated bed drag chain and on my printer I could borrow one without losing its function. The cable harness needs to be approximately 3-5cm longer, the cables are more than long enough they just needs to be slightly rearranged. Direction of the extruder stepper motors needs to be reversed, I changed the direction by switching place of the outer wires by using a needle to release the connectors. Firmware needs to be updated to the correct value based on your stepper motors resolution. 417,5 steps for the 1,8deg and 835 steps for the 0,9deg motor. When changing the firmware, remember the dual extruder option in Configuration H I missed this one on my first update. Extruder stepper controller voltage needs to be adjusted to the correct value, based on which stepper motor you are using. I used approximately 45% of the rated current in voltage, 0,8A and 0,355V.

Hardware needed:
2x Titan extruders for donor parts, http://e3d-online.com/Titan-Extruder

(There is a cheaper solution to by the parts separately, but the spring can’t be bought separately from E3D. Here are the spring data supplied by E3D: http://springsdirect.co.uk/product/s-211/
You will also need extra bearings 2x 3x10x4 and 4x MR95ZZ and 200mm of PTFE tubing for 1.75mm filament)

4x Bearings 5x9x3 (MR95ZZ), http://e3d-online.com/Mechanical/Motion/MR95ZZ
8x DIN 912 M3x30 Hex socket head screws, Hardware store
2x DIN 912 M3x16 Hex socket head screws, Hardware store
10x DIN 6798 A3.2 serrated lock washers, Hardware store
4x DIN 934 M3 Hex nuts, Hardware store
2x DIN 7991 M3x16 Countersunk hex head screw, Hardware store
2x DIN 7991 M3x10 Countersunk hex head screw, Hardware store
2x DIN 7991 M4x16 Countersunk hex head screw, Hardware store
2x DIN 125 A6.4 Plain washer, Hardware store
2x NEMA 17 stepper motors of your choice, I used these stepper motors: http://www.robotdigg.com/product/6/NEMA17-Stepper-Motor-34mm-Long,-0.8A. Original motors can be used but I strongly recommend switching them for a lighter alternative and these motor have different polarity than the regular motors I used (original motors are like the Wanhao motors).

Printing of the parts:
All parts where printed in ABS plastic, but any plastic than can withstand 75-80 °C will do.
Printed with 0.4mm nozzle, 50mm/s, 0.2mm layer height, 2 shells 3 shells for the extruder body, 5 solid bottom and top layers 25-30% infill, some changes here will depend on the stiffness of the filament used. All parts except for the filament guides need support, I used 2mm columns due to the small details.

Preparation and assembly:
Preparation with threaded taps (M3, M6 ore 1/8 Pipe thread), drill bits (3, 3.5, 4, 4.2 and 6mm) and other tools to make all parts move smoothly are required. Drill with a 4mm drill bit about 10mm down in the original filament guides and 3-4mm down in the push fit connector to ensure a smooth filament transition. Remove the filament guides or remove the nozzle before drilling to ensure that no debris get stuck in the nozzle. I used the motor gear as a drill bit stopper to ensure that I didn’t drilled to deep into the filament guides.
Cut and fit the PTFE tubing in the correct lengths, this length will depend on how deep you drill into the guides.

Hopefully I have covered all the details needed to use this design and I have also included the STEP files for the extruder parts. The internal parts I used in this design I found at Grabcad: https://grabcad.com/library/e3d-titan-extruder-2

Thanks to Ben Neubauer for a brilliant 3D model of the E3D Titan extruder.

Happy Printing!

title: Automatic Bike Brake Light
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is an automatic back light for electric bicycle. I wanted it to work without switches for the brake levers so I used an accelerometer.

The software can be found here: https://github.com/ChristophPech/BrakeLight

The LEDs are powered through a Mosfet and the Arduino's PWM controls brightness for normal operation and braking state.

The accelerometer is polled at 2kHz then accumulated to 10Hz and put through a band pass filter to remove noise (low pass) and align to the normal orientation (high pass)

You can use any logic level Mosfet, the pull-down and gate resistors are not strictly necessary but without them I got some glitches with my cheap Chinese nano clone. The status LED can be omitted too but it is useful to see if it works, the on board LED cannot be used when using SPI.

Depending on you input Voltage you might want to add 5V DC converter for the Arduino because it can handle no more than 12V (my cheap Chinese clone didn't work reliably with 12V either)

  • Arduino Nano (or Mini or Micro)
  • N-Channel logic level Mosfet: (e.g. RFP30N06LE)
  • 12V COB-Led module (e.g. Sumbulbs )
  • Adxl345 (Sparkfun breakout)
  • Red rectangular back reflectors

title: Yet another Bezier library for OpenSCAD

description.text:
This is yet another Bezier library, which takes a list of nodes and control points and generates a list of points that you can then feed into polygon() or some other function. The Bezier curves can be either 2D or 3D, but I've only been using it for 2D.

The library is designed so one can lay out 2D Bezier curves basically in one's head.

One of the things I wanted was the ability to have an easy way to include smooth control points--control points that ensure that curve through the node has no cusp.

To use, first do use <bezier.scad>; and then call the function Bezier(pointList) to generate output points. There is an optional precision=x parameter. With that parameter, about 1/x points will be generated per segment (excepting 2D segments that are a straight line--these are optimized to two points). Default is precision=0.05.

The pointList is a list of points arranged as follows:
[node,control,control,node,control,control,node,...]
I recommend that in your code you flag the control points with /*C*/ so you don't get lost in a long list of points.

Each segment of the Bezier curve consists of two nodes, with two control points in between them. You can also have these special control points:

  • SYMMETRIC(): This makes the control point be on the same line and at the same distance to the node as the control point on the other side

  • SMOOTH_REL(x): This is like SYMMETRIC() except that the distance of the control point to the node is x times the distance of the other control point to the node (can be negative for special effects); SYMMETRIC() is in fact shorthand for SMOOTH_REL(1)

  • SMOOTH_ABS(x): This is like SYMMETRIC() except that the distance of the control point to the node is exactly x (can be negative for special effects)

  • OFFSET(v): This makes the control point be at the neighboring node plus the vector v

  • POLAR(r,angle): Like OFFSET(v) but specified in polar coordinates; equivalent to OFFSET(r*[cos(angle),sin(angle)]); only works in 2D

  • SHARP(): Puts the control point at the neighboring node; equivalent to OFFSET([0,0]) (or OFFSET([0,0,0]))

You can't have SMOOTH_*() and/or SYMMETRIC() control points on both sides of a node--the library then wouldn't know which line to place the control points on.

Finally, at the end of your list of points (and only there) you can add one or more REPEAT_MIRRORED(normalVector) points each of which stitches at the end of the path what came before but reflects it in the direction of the normalVector. For instance, if you want to draw a rounded plus sign, you can just include the first quarter, and then two REPEAT_MIRRORED() items.

There is also a utility function DecodeSpecialBezierPoints(p) which takes a node/control point list p and decodes all the special points (SMOOTH_*(), etc.) into ordinary 2D vectors. This is useful if, say, you want to take a Bezier curve and transform it in some way.

See the sample polygons in the source code for examples.

A useful included module for debugging Bezier curves is BezierVisualize(p).

Updates: Support for 3D curves.

title: Learning Blade 3D Maker Quest - Wind Turbine Model

description.text:
These are the supporting files for the Learning Blade Wind Turbine Model.

This Maker Quest gives students practice designing new blades for a wind turbine. The model files in this lesson can be assembled into a simple wind turbine. However, the main purpose of the exercise is to design new turbine blade models. Once the students have designed and printed their turbine blades, they will measure and compare their blades’ efficiency.

Have you ever considered how exciting the future of energy production will be? As renewable energy becomes more common, it’s important to keep exploring ways to make energy production more efficient.
This exercise gives students practice designing new blades for a wind turbine. The model files in this lesson can be assembled into a simple wind turbine. However, the main purpose of the exercise is to design new turbine blade models. Once the students have designed and printed their turbine blades, they will measure and compare their blades’ efficiency.

Students should identify and download the files for this exercise to their computer.
After downloading, the model file for the turbine blades will need to be customized. There is a file for a sample turbine blade (Turbine Blade.stl) so students can see an example of how the blade will look and connect to the turbine nosecone. Students may either modify that file, or start from the blank blade base file (Turbine Blade base.stl) included in the project files collection.
Students may use any 3D modeling software they’re comfortable with to make their own turbine blades. TinkerCad.com is a popular, free 3D modeling application that most students will find easy to use. Regardless of which 3D modeling software the students use, they should be sure to connect their blade design to the blade base provided. This will ensure the students’ designs connect easily to the rest of the wind turbine components.
Once the files are ready to print, students should import them into the 3D slicing software. The individual components of the wind turbine are designed to print within a 100 mm x 100 mm x 100 mm print volume. The components could be scaled, but the turbine tower is designed to work with a standard #2 pencil and 2-liter bottle, so any changes in scale could affect the fit of the components.
Once the slicing software has prepared the printing instructions, all of the turbine components should be printed and carefully removed from the printing surface. Make sure to print three copies of each student’s turbine blades.
Begin the turbine assembly by filling the bottom 4 inches of the 2-liter bottle with the rocks, sand, or water. Then, screw the turbine tower onto the 2-liter bottle.
Use the permanent marker to fil in the groove in the round speed indicator disc. Slide the disc onto the #2 pencil, then slide the turbine bushing onto the pencil as shown.
Insert the pencil into the hole atop the turbine tower so the bushing is completely inside the tower hole. The pencil should be able to spin freely within the hole.
Next, push the turbine nosecone onto the end of the pencil as shown.
Now you may insert the students’ turbine blades into the slots in the front of the turbine nosecone. The blades should slide into the nosecone slots and fit snugly. Testing the Efficiency of a Blade Design
Each set of turbine blades will be tested to see how quickly they can cause the turbine’s speed indicator disc travel through four complete rotations.
Begin a test by making sure all of the turbine blades are firmly seated.
Next, place the electric fan 6 inches from the wind turbine.
Rotate the pencil until the mark on the speed indicator disc is pointing straight up. Hold the pencil in place until the test begins.
Have someone prepare the stopwatch and switch on the electric fan. You should still be holding the pencil and keeping it from spinning.
Once the electric fan has spun up to speed, start the stopwatch and release the pencil at the same time.
Watch the speed indicator disc and stop the stopwatch once the disc completes four rotations.
Turn off the fan and record the time it took the turbine to spin 4 rotations.
Each student’s set of turbine blades should be tested in the same manner, making sure the conditions of the tests are as precisely the same as possible. To reduce the effect of testing inconsistencies, and if time permits, each set of blades could be tested multiple times and an average time to four rotations used to represent each students’ blade design. Students should also calculate the Revolutions Per Minute (RPM) their turbine blades achieved. RPM is a good standard for comparing rotational speed. Additional Ideas
Once all of the blade designs have been tested, students could be allowed to redesign their blades. They should consider which blade designs performed the best and worst, and use that evaluation to help redesign their blades. Once the second round of blades have been tested, ask the students to discuss why they made the changes they made. Also, have them discuss how the overall blade performance changed in the second round of testing.

An empty 2-liter bottle
Rocks, sand, or water (to weight down the bottle)
An unsharpened #2 pencil
A stopwatch

A modification of
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9313 I've expanded the diameters of the main component's openings each by 3.6mm(to 11.8mm) to allow for small extruded rings of 11mm diameter on the handwheel and the lens counter gear to make direct contact with the 608 bearings. This way, the two M8 bolts can snugly sandwich together the bevel gear, the bearing, and the lens counter gear or handwheel, so the whole assemblies might be more securely held together. Also, the extruded rings would discourage friction from the handwheel or lens counter gear from occurring against the main frame component. The addition of the rings will make printing a bit more tricky. Supports will be needed for whatever orientation you decide to print in. To make printing easier, or to save you from reprinting the parts if you already have printed the original version, you may opt to keep the original handwheel and lens counter gear and instead simply use the 1.2mm and 2.4mm rings to do the job. There shouldn't be a difference. The parts Gear_new_repariert.stl and MiddlePiece.stl are unchanged from the original design. The handwheel that I modified with the ring is that made by Litwan.
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9577 I have yet to try either the original design or this design myself yet because I don't personally own a printer, but upon my inspection, it looks to me that this might work better. Please tell me if so!

There are two options for printing this modification.  
The first option is to print the modified handwheel and lens counter gear that I have here. The drawback to this is that the ring I've added to them will require the addition of supports for a proper print. Also, if you already have the original model, you will have to reprint these parts just for the addition of the tiny rings.  
Alternately, you can use the original handwheel and lens counter gear parts and simply add the 1.2mm and 2.4mm rings to the handwheel and lens counter gear sandwiches, respectively. This will be much less of a hassle to print, and might save you a lot of time if you've already made the original model; as you would only have to reprint the main component.
